        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-12-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-07-26T23:00:00-05:00" n="454" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d454">
                <head>454. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At 8:40 a.m. on November 1 Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName> telephoned President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName>. Their conversation went as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The <gloss target="#t_Sec1">Sec</gloss>. said we are going to have to
                            make important decisions here today and don’t know how much time we
                            should spend at <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>. There is the
                            question of our attitude toward the possible sanctions against the
                            Israelis and the <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> meets at 5. The
                                <gloss target="#t_Sec1">Sec</gloss>. would like time with the Pres.
                            this a.m. <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> is mostly about the policy
                            for satellite countries which the <gloss target="#t_Sec1">Sec</gloss>.
                            thinks is academic as the situation has pretty much taken <gloss
                                target="#t_CARE1">care</gloss> of itself. The <gloss
                                target="#t_Sec1">Sec</gloss>. will make a report on Suez and the
                            Pres. said it would be a good thing to have a general discussion re the
                                <gloss target="#t_ME1">ME</gloss>. The Pres. referred to what
                            Lippmann said and the <gloss target="#t_Sec1">Sec</gloss>. said he has
                            not written anything favorable for 4 years and his facts are wrong. The
                            Pres. also referred to what <persName corresp="#p_SA1"
                                >Stevenson</persName> said. The Pres. said we should not do anything
                            that makes us look as if we are trying to get an excuse to pick on
                            Israel. If we do anything against them, then we have to do something
                            against Fr and Br. The <gloss target="#t_Sec1">Sec</gloss>. referred to
                            the statement re living up to the Tripartite Agreement. If we give aid
                            to Israel when she is an aggressor it makes a mockery of everything. We
                            have to have a position by 5.” (Eisenhower Library, Dulles Papers, White
                            House Telephone Conversations)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0942" n="902" xml:id="pg_902"/>
                <p>Another memorandum of this telephone conversation, prepared in the Office of the
                    President, is <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., Whitman File, Eisenhower Diaries.
                    The memorandum of discussion of the November 1 meeting of the National Security
                    Council is <ref target="#d455">
                        <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>
                    </ref>. The syndicated column by <persName>Walter Lippman</persName> to which
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> referred was entitled
                    “Disaster in the Middle East” and appeared in the <hi rend="italic">Washington
                        Post</hi> on November 1.</p>
